  footnotes: []
english:
  title: 'An Idle Evening: A Chance Verse with Jung-nyeo at My Leisure Study'
  author: Byeon Jung-ryang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Snow melts away and spring's light stirs to life,
    Mountains encircle us as dusk gathers thick.
    Lazy by nature, my livelihood remains meager—
    yet in this leisure, I cherish visiting old friends.

    The ancient well releases its frozen grip at last,
    the cold plum branch bears its first delicate flowers.
    Such simple joy and taste suffice for us—
    we buy our wine and brew our tea again.
  footnotes:
    - Jung-nyeo (중려) likely refers to a companion or fellow scholar with whom the poet shares this moment of leisure and contemplation.
    - The imagery of melting snow, spring light, and budding plums creates a metaphorical parallel between nature's renewal and the warmth of human companionship and simple pleasures.
    - The poem celebrates the virtue of poverty and idleness as conditions that enable genuine friendship and aesthetic appreciation, reflecting Neo-Confucian scholarly ideals.
